717065f.text:
Broadway, at, adjoining and north of the N. W. corner of Liberty Street (left, not shown, showing the site of the later date Singer Building.
No. 161 Broadway, the five story building contains, the Knickerbocker Life Insurance Co., the Columbia Fire Insurance Co., and the Yonkers-New York Fire Insurance Co. The 1atter might be the re-organized firm consisting of the separate companies that failed in the Boston fire of 1871. This structure was the home of the Greenwich Insurance Co. in the 1890's. An illustration showing this occupancy appears on page 643 of Moses Kings Handbook of New York, 1893. The Wlliamsburg City Fire Insurance Co. occupies the store of No. 165. This firm was organized in 1853. They later moved to their newly completed (about 1885) home across the street
(N. E. corner of Liberty St.)
For purposes of information, the various remaining insurance companies after the fire of 1835 were required to organize individually and were prohibited from accumulating functions. They were required to be chartered for specific purposes, such as fire, life, fidelity, casualty, etc. On the repeal of the Act of 1829, many foreign firms (mainly English) entered this field. After the second conflagration in the business center of New York (1845), an association of city underwriters was formed that developed into the National Board in 1866.

717030f.text:
Broadway (right), east side, south from Cedar to Pine Streets, showing ravages of the fire of January 9, 1912 that destroyed the old Equitable Building. Securities worth half a billion dollars remained in the vaults after the fire. Several advocates suggested the utilization of this site as a park but land prices prohibited same and the present 38-story structure
was erected.

The photographer is viewing southward from the
16-story building at No. 128 Broadway. Above the ruins towers the 21-story American Surety Company Building (No. 96-100 Broadway). To the right is the spire of Trinity Church.

1912
